18 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
19 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
20 Article – Election Law
21 1–101.
22 (a) In this article the following words have the meanings indicated unless a
23 different meaning is clearly intended from the context.
24 (j) “Campaign manager” means a person designated by a candidate[,] or [the
25 candidate’s representative,] CHAIR OF A CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY to exercise general
26 overall responsibility for the conduct of the candidate’s political campaign.
27 (mm) “Responsible officers” means the [chairman] CHAIR and treasurer of a
28 political committee.
29 2–301.
30 (b) (1) An individual subject to this section may not, while holding the position:
31 (iii) except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, as to any
32 candidate or any matter that is subject to an election under this article:
33 1. be a campaign manager;

SENATE BILL 153 3
1 2. be a treasurer [or subtreasurer] for a campaign finance
2 entity; or
3 3. take any other active part in political management or a
4 political campaign.
5 13–207.
6 (c) To establish a political committee:
7 (1) a [chairman] CHAIR and a treasurer shall be appointed on a form that
8 the State Board prescribes and that is signed by the [chairman] CHAIR and treasurer and
9 includes:
10 (i) the residence addresses of the [chairman] CHAIR and the
11 treasurer;
12 (ii) if the [chairman] CHAIR and treasurer affirmatively consent to
13 receiving notice under this title only by electronic mail, the electronic mail address of the
14 [chairman] CHAIR and the treasurer; and
15 (iii) the information required by § 13–208 of this subtitle; and
16 (2) the form shall be filed with the State Board.
17 (3) THE CANDIDATE SHALL APPOINT THE CHAIR AND TREASURER OF
18 AN AUTHORIZED CANDIDATE CAMPAIGN COMMITTEE.
19 (3) (4) The [chairman] CHAIR or treasurer of a political committee shall
20 notify the State Board of a change in the residence address of the [chairman] CHAIR or
21 treasurer no later than 21 days before the day on which the political committee’s next
22 campaign finance report is due under § 13–309 of this title.
23 (4) (5) The [chairman] CHAIR or treasurer of a political committee shall
24 notify the State Board of a change in the electronic mail address of the [chairman] CHAIR
25 or treasurer by the date specified in paragraph (3) of this subsection if the [chairman]
26 CHAIR and treasurer of the political committee have affirmatively consented to receiving
27 notice under this title only by electronic mail.
28 (d) (1) A [chairman] CHAIR or treasurer of a political committee may resign
29 by completing a resignation form that the State Board prescribes and filing the form with
30 the State Board.

4 SENATE BILL 153
1 (2) If a vacancy occurs in the office of [chairman] CHAIR or the office of
2 treasurer, the political committee promptly shall appoint a new [chairman] CHAIR or
3 treasurer in accordance with this section.
4 (3) A political committee may not receive or disburse money or any other
5 thing of value if there is a vacancy in the office of [chairman] CHAIR or the office of
6 treasurer.
7 13–212.
8 [An individual] A CANDIDATE, CANDIDATE’S REPRESENTATIVE, OR CHAIR OF A
9 CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY may appoint a campaign manager by:
10 (1) completing a form that the State Board prescribes and that includes the
11 name and address of that campaign manager; and
12 (2) filing the form with the [board where the individual is required to file
13 a certificate of candidacy] STATE BOARD.
14 13–215.
15 (a) Each [chairman] CHAIR, AND treasurer, and campaign manager shall be a
16 registered voter of the State.
17 (b) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection, a candidate may not act:
18 (i) as the treasurer of a campaign finance entity of the candidate; or
19 (ii) with respect to any other campaign finance entity:
20 1. as [the campaign manager or treasurer] A RESPONSIBLE
21 OFFICER; or
22 2. in any other position that exercises general overall
23 responsibility for the conduct of the entity.
24 (2) (i) An incumbent member of a central committee who is a candidate
25 for election to party office may act as a responsible officer of that central committee.
26 (ii) With respect to any campaign finance entity other than the
27 candidate’s own campaign finance entity, a candidate for delegate to the Democratic
28 National Convention or a candidate for delegate to the Republican National Convention may
29 act:

SENATE BILL 153 5
1 1. as [the campaign manager or treasurer] A RESPONSIBLE
2 OFFICER; or
3 2. in any other position that exercises general overall
4 responsibility for the conduct of the entity.
5 (c) Subject to subsection (b) of this section, the [chairman] CHAIR, treasurer, or
6 campaign manager of a campaign finance entity may serve as the [chairman] CHAIR,
7 treasurer, or campaign manager of another campaign finance entity.
8 13–218.
9 (a) THE TREASURER IS THE FINANCIAL STEWARD OF THE CAMPAIGN
10 FINANCE ENTITY.
11 (B) All assets received by or on behalf of a campaign finance entity shall be:
12 (1) delivered to AND MANAGED BY the [treasurer] CAMPAIGN FINANCE
13 ENTITY; [and]
14 (2) maintained by the treasurer for the purposes of the campaign finance
15 entity;
16 (3) ACCOUNTED FOR IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 13–221 OF THIS
17 SUBTITLE; AND
18 (4) CONSIDERED OWNED BY THE CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY.
19 [(b)] (C) (1) Assets of a campaign finance entity may be disbursed only:
20 (i) if [they have passed through the hands of the treasurer]
21 ACCOUNTED FOR IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 13–221 OF THIS SUBTITLE; and
22 (ii) in accordance with the purposes of the entity AND THIS TITLE.
23 (2) Subject to § 13–220(b)(2) and (c) of this subtitle and except as provided
24 in subsection [(d)] (E) of this section, the treasurer shall approve all disbursements for the
25 campaign finance entity.
26 [(c)] (D) (1) The treasurer of a State or county central committee of a political
27 party may not approve any disbursement of the central committee’s assets, or incur any
28 liability on its behalf, without authority and direction from the [chairman] CHAIR of the
29 central committee.

6 SENATE BILL 153
1 (2) THE TREASURER OF A POLITICAL ACTION COMMITTEE OF A
2 POLITICAL PARTY MAY NOT APPROVE ANY DISBURSEMENT OF THE POLITICAL
3 ACTION COMMITTEE’S ASSETS, OR INCUR ANY LIABILITY ON ITS BEHALF, WITHOUT
4 AUTHORITY AND DIRECTION FROM THE CHAIR OF THE POLITICAL ACTION
5 COMMITTEE.
6 [(d)] (E) [(1) If the treasurer of a campaign finance entity is temporarily
7 unable to perform the duties of the office, the chairman of the campaign finance entity may
8 approve a disbursement on behalf of the campaign finance entity in the same manner as
9 the treasurer.
10 (2) If the chairman approves a disbursement under this subsection, within
11 7 days after approving the disbursement, the chairman shall submit a report to the
12 treasurer for the account book of the campaign finance entity, including:
13 (i) a statement of the expenditure approved under the authority of
14 the chairman;
15 (ii) the name and address of the person to whom the expenditure was
16 made;
17 (iii) the purpose for which the expenditure was made; and
18 (iv) a copy of the receipt for the expenditure that was made.]
19 (1) THE TREASURER A CANDIDATE OR THE RESPONSIBLE OFFICERS
20 MAY DESIGNATE AUTHORIZED AGENTS OF THE CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY TO MAKE
21 DISBURSEMENTS CARRY OUT DUTIES ON BEHALF OF AND IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE
22 PURPOSE OF THE CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY.
23 (2) THE DESIGNATION OF AN AUTHORIZED AGENT MUST BE MADE IN
24 WRITING BEFORE THE FIRST DISBURSEMENT IS MADE BY THE AUTHORIZED AGENT.
25 (3) ANY ACTION TAKEN BY THE DESIGNATED AUTHORIZED AGENT ON
26 BEHALF OF THE CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY IS THE RESPONSIBILITY OF THE
27 TREASURER.
28 (4) A DESIGNATED AUTHORIZED AGENT:
29 (I) HAS A FIDUCIARY DUTY TO THE CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY
30 FOR THE AGENT’S CONDUCT IN MAKING DISBURSEMENTS ON BEHALF OF THE
31 CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY; AND

SENATE BILL 153 7
1 (II) SHALL CONFIRM THE AGENT’S UNDERSTANDING OF THE
2 FIDUCIARY DUTY BY SIGNING THE WRITTEN DESIGNATION THAT INCLUDES A
3 STATEMENT OF THE DUTY.
4 (5) (2) A DESIGNATED AUTHORIZED AGENT MAY ASSIST THE
5 TREASURER IN THE PREPARATION OF ANY REQUIRED FILINGS WITH THE STATE
6 BOARD.
7 [(3)] (6) (3) A [chairman who is a] candidate may not [approve] HAVE A
8 CANDIDATE MAY NOT ACCESS TO, OR MAKE a disbursement for a campaign finance
9 entity FROM, FUNDS DEPOSITED IN THE DESIGNATED CAMPAIGN ACCOUNT
10 ESTABLISHED UNDER § 13–220 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
11 (4) A CANDIDATE SHALL HAVE KNOWLEDGE OF ALL DISBURSEMENTS
12 MADE FROM THE DESIGNATED CAMPAIGN ACCOUNT OF THE CANDIDATE’S
13 AUTHORIZED CANDIDATE CAMPAIGN COMMITTEE.
14 13–220.
15 (e) Within 30 days after filing a campaign finance report at the State Board, the
16 treasurer of an authorized candidate campaign committee shall provide both the candidate
17 and the [chairman] CHAIR with a copy of the most recent campaign account bank
18 statement.
19 13–246.
20 A person who claims that money is due from a campaign finance entity shall present
21 a claim for payment to the treasurer [or subtreasurer] not later than 30 days after the
22 election for which the liability was incurred.
23 13–248.
24 If a responsible officer of a campaign finance entity has a compensation agreement
25 with the campaign finance entity, before making a disbursement for the compensation, the
26 campaign finance entity shall submit to the State Board:
27 (1) a copy of the compensation agreement; and
28 (2) if the campaign finance entity is an authorized candidate campaign
29 committee, the written consent of the candidate.
30 13–304.
31 (b) A campaign finance report filed by a campaign finance entity under subsection
32 (a) of this section shall include:

8 SENATE BILL 153
1 (1) the information required by the State Board with respect to all
2 contributions received and all expenditures made by or on behalf of the campaign finance
3 entity during the designated reporting period; [and]
4 (2) the information regarding the occupations and employers of
5 contributors required to be recorded by the treasurer of a campaign finance entity under §
6 13–221 of this title; AND
7 (3) THE WRITTEN DESIGNATIONS NAMING THE AUTHORIZED AGENTS
8 WHO MAY ACT ON THE TREASURER’S BEHALF, IF ANY.
9 13–604.1.
10 (b) The State Board may impose a civil penalty in accordance with this section for
11 the following violations:
12 (1) making a disbursement in a manner not [authorized in § 13–218(b)(2),
13 (c), and (d)] IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 13–218(C)(2), (D), AND (E)(6) (E)(3) of this title;
14 (d) (1) Except as otherwise provided in this title or as provided in paragraph
15 (2) of this subsection, the amount of a civil penalty imposed under this section may not
16 exceed $1,000 for each violation.
17 (2) As to a violation of § 13–235 of this title, the campaign finance entity
18 that receives a contribution as a result of a violation shall:
19 (i) refund the contribution to the contributor; and
20 (ii) pay a civil penalty that equals $1,000 plus the amount of the
21 contribution, unless the State Board at its discretion assesses a lesser penalty for good
22 cause.
23 (3) AS TO A VIOLATION OF § 13–218(E)(2) OR § 13–248 OF THIS TITLE,
24 THE CAMPAIGN FINANCE ENTITY OR OTHER PERSON THAT COMMITTED THE
25 VIOLATION SHALL PAY A CIVIL PENALTY THAT EQUALS $1,000 PLUS THE AMOUNT
26 OF THE DISBURSEMENT MADE WITHOUT THE REQUIRED APPROVAL.
27 (f) (1) Subject to paragraphs (2) and (3) of this subsection, a civil penalty
28 imposed under this section shall be paid by the campaign finance entity.
29 (2) If the campaign finance entity has insufficient funds with which to pay
30 the full amount of the civil penalty in a timely manner, after the campaign account of the
31 finance entity is exhausted the balance of the civil penalty is the joint and several liability
32 of the responsible officers.

SENATE BILL 153 9
1 (3) If a violation is committed by a person not acting on behalf of, or at the
2 request or suggestion of, a candidate or a campaign finance entity, the civil penalty shall
3 be paid by the person who committed the violation.
4 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
5 January 1, 2027.
